dspace-development.title: DataSpace is inaccessible for the morning of 08/08/23

comments.body:
Once authenticated over the VPN, I find that I can access the website:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/5923260e-b3dd-4dd0-8e49-0ee5a1c1dc52)
The user confirmed at 08:18AM EST that the service has been restored. I am uncertain as to what triggered the service downtime, as I did not restart any services or reboot the VM.

This has been restored, it appears that the `postgresql` system service had been halted or failed:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/5d693342-1643-4e73-b5c9-08aeb123faa0)
The runlevels for `postgresql` needed to be set for 3,4,5 in order to ensure that these would start for both the `QA` and `production` environments.

Calculate storage requirements for VectorResource derivatives

comments.body:
The total space on disk of all zipped VectorResource shapefiles is approximately: **160.41 GB**

Script used to sum up file sizes:

```ruby
query_service = ChangeSetPersister.default.query_service
vector_resources = query_service.find_all_of_model(model: VectorResource); nil
count = vector_resources.count
i = 0
vector_resources.map do |v|
  i += 1
  puts "#{i}/#{count}"
  gms = v.decorate.geo_members
  if gms.present?
    gms[0].size[0].to_i
  else
    0
  end
rescue
  0
end.reduce(:+)
```

New experiment: Determine the difference is size between the zipped Shapefiles and the same data loaded in postgres.

1. Initial postgres database size: 15 MB
2. 10 random PUL shapefile zips. Size: 86.2 MB
3. Size of database after ingesting shapefiles: 183 MB
4. Difference: 183 - 86.2 - 15 = 81.8 MB
  - Storing in postgres roughly doubles the required space
  - ((183 - 15) / 86.2) * 100 = 194%
6. Expected size of current shapefiles when loaded into postgres: **320 GB**

princeton_ansible.title: [nginx] special handling for rate-limited traffic on the catalog

comments.body:
Tested successfully today. To test rate-limiting, we:
1. installed `siege` on a laptop with `brew install siege`
2. disconnected from the VPN (VPN traffic is never rate-limited)
3. created a file called `combined` that contained a long list of URLs in the catalog
4. ran `siege --delay=0.1 --file=combined --internet --verbose --reps=100 --concurrent=20`
5. while the `siege` command was still running, opened a catalog page in a browser to view the error results
